nse of their control over the process. In the end, the insights of the story offer hope. Written for a broad audience and supported by an array of photographs and graphics, Standing in the Need offers readers an inside view of life at its most vulnerable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aDisaster victims -- Louisiana -- New Orleans -- Biography. 0aDisaster victimszLouisianazNew OrleansvBiography. 0aHurricane Katrina, 2005 -- Social aspects. 0aHurricane Katrina, 2005xSocial aspects. 0aRefugees -- Louisiana -- New Orleans -- Social conditions. 0aRefugeeszLouisianazNew OrleansxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/30728140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477307380423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477307380/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK